Aluoch said it’s their intention to have the team proceed to camp from Monday next week, since they want more para-athletes to qualify for Tokyo."Having them in camp will ensure that they stay away from many distractions, besides also giving them ample time to train, noting that they have stayed for long without training owing to Covid-19 situation," said Aluoch. The National Paralympic Committee of Kenya (KNPC) will take 37 athletes, 12 guides and 15 officials to the 2021 Dubai Athletics Para Grand Prix due February 7-14.
At the same time, KNPC will require Sh26 million to successfully take part in the Dubai event that will form part of the Tokyo Olympic Games qualification.



