Aluoch said it’s their intention to have the team proceed to camp from Monday next week, since they want more para-athletes to qualify for Tokyo.
"Having them in camp will ensure that they stay away from many distractions, besides also giving them ample time to train, noting that they have stayed for long without training owing to Covid-19 situation," said Aluoch.
So far, four Kenyans have qualified for Tokyo Olympics, 2016 Rio Paralympics 5,000m T11 champion Samwel Muchai, Nancy Chelagat, Hellen Wawira (powerlifting) and Asia Mohammed (Para-rower).
“The numbers are bound to increase with more qualifying events line up. More so, we shall only take athletes who will have shown good form hence qualifying alone isn’t the ticket,” warned Aluoch.



